===Physical===

Ing Bataan Malapulu metung mabatung makasuglung ka reng [[bunduk ning Zamabales]] king [[Luzon]], [[Filipinas]]. Kakakwani ne ing It separates the [[Manila Bay]] from the [[South China Sea]]. The peninsula features Mount Natib (1,253 m) in the north and the Mariveles Mountains in the south, which includes [[Mount Samat]], the location of the historical marker for the [[Bataan Death March]].

==Amlat o Kasalesayan==

===Mumunang Amlat===

The province of Bataan was established in [[1754]] by Governor-General Pedro Manuel Arandia out of territories belonging to [[Pampanga]] and the ''corregimiento'' of [[Mariveles, Bataan|Mariveles]] which, at the time, included [[Maragondon, Cavite]] across the [[Manila Bay]].

In [[1647]], [[Netherlands|Dutch]] naval forces landed in country in an attempt to seize the islands from [[Spain]]. The forces massacred the people of [[Abucay, Bataan|Abucay]] in Bataan. In the late 1700s, [[Limahong]], a Chinese pirate used Bataan as the launching point for his conquest of [[Luzon]], which was unsuccessful.

===Meto-Yatung Labanan===

Bataan featured prominently during [[World War II]]. Prior to the [[1941]] [[Japan]]ese invasion, the [[United States Army|US Army]] stored nearly 1,000,000 US [[gallon]]s (3,800 m&sup3;) of [[gasoline]] here.

Shortly after the Japanese Army invaded the country in December [[1941]], the combined forces of Filipino and US forces were being gradually overrun and [[Douglas MacArthur|General Douglas MacArthur]] decided to make Bataan the site of a last stand. (See [[Battle of the Philippines (1941-42)]]. On [[January 7]], [[1942]], Japanese forces started the siege of the peninsula. On [[April 3]] the Japanese began an all-out assault on the American and Filipino troops left on the peninsula. Bataan fell on [[April 9]] and the [[Bataan Death March]] began. About 70,000 captured American and Filipino soldiers were forced to march more than a hundred kilometers from Bataan to [[Tarlac]].

